Credit Card Brand Attribute Ratings

Mark Preston

December 2, 2018

Introduction: Examining brand attribute ratings and consumer preferences

In this analysis, Ill use consumer survey data collected on individual credit card company preferences. This brand strategy data provides a forum for consumers to provide feedback on how they feel about certain banking products. Overall, this analysis will work towards building models that establish a relationship between the brand attribute ratings consumers provided and their preference ratings for credit cards.

Before proceeding with the work, Ill highlight data transformations which I performed. Most notably, the initial data set has unclear, non-descriptive column names. The columns are the primarily comprised of the brand attribute ratings so I felt it was essential to better label these. As such, Ive provided more descriptive column names. Beyond this, Ive changed the missing data values from -99 to 0 (after altering the zero values for the pri_sec column for consistency) and added the brand names for each credit card.

Linear model with brand ratings: Structural problems and multicollinearity

One method for assessing the relationship between brand ratings and preference is regression. However, this approach is difficult owing to a few issues. First, the brand rating data are generally quite noisy owing to a small scale (1 to 4) which can create a lot of variance between respondent answers.

Additionally, the set has extremely high multicollinearity. The correlation plot below shows that each variable has very high correlation with almost every other variable. Again, this is largely because all the values are positive and closely aligned to begin with, which inherently introduces this structure. The introduction of multicollinearity inflates standard errors and therefore, will negatively impact any regression modelling.

cc_brands %>%
  select(7:38) %>%
  cor() %>%
  corrplot(type = "upper")

Just to highlight this, Ive developed a linear model with all the brand ratings. The plot below shows the predictions are erratic and at times nowhere near correct. That said, there is a heavier concentration of points below 3, which indicates there are predictions that might be useable.

profiles <- c(seq(1, nrow(cc_brands), 9), seq(5, nrow(cc_brands), 9)) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  rename(holdout = ".") %>%
  arrange(holdout)

brand_train <- cc_brands %>%
  select(1, 7:38) %>%
  filter(!row_number() %in% profiles$holdout)

brand_test <- cc_brands %>%
  select(1, 7:38) %>%
  filter(row_number() %in% profiles$holdout)

To formalize how impactuful the multicollinearity is, Ive included a variance inflation factor (VIF) chart for the model. These values provide an estimate for how much the regression coefficients are inflated. As a rule of thumb, a VIF greater than 4 signals high multicollinearity while values over 10 highlight extreme levels. As seen below, the lowest value is above four and numerous variables are above 10. This means some corrections need to take place so any modelling result can be interpretable.

PCA regression and factor analysis with brand data

To effectively deal with the sets multicollinearity, principle components analysis (PCA) is a reasonable solution. The method orthogonalizes the input data resulting in predictors that are uncorrelated. Additionally, the information from numerous columns can be compacted into fewer variables so there are fewer variables to work with (dimensional reduction). To begin this process, Ive conducted PCA on the predictors here. As a note, I elected not to transform the variables since they are all on the same rating scale.

Selecting the correct number of factors here can be accomplished using a scree plot. The visualization shows a definite break at seven components. That said, the first principle component captures 89% of the variance with only 1% increases thereafter. As such, I think taking seven is too many as PCA2 to PCA7 only capture 6% of the variance. Im going to carry forward the first three, which still captures a very high 91% of variance. As always, in a business setting this approach would need to be verified with the brand manager to ensure this was reasonable.

brand_pca <- princomp(x = cc_brands[,8:38])

data.frame(dev = brand_pca$sdev ^ 2) %>%
  rownames_to_column(var = "PC") %>%
  mutate(variance_exp = round(dev / (sum(dev)), 2),
         vaf = cumsum(variance_exp),
         PC = str_replace(string = PC, pattern = "Comp.", replacement = "PCA"),
         vaf_line = "line") %>%
  slice(1:9) %>%
  ggplot(aes(PC, vaf, group = vaf_line, label = paste0(vaf * 100,"%"))) +
  geom_line(colour = "royalblue2", size = 1.3) +
  geom_label(hjust = 0, nudge_x = 0.15, nudge_y = 0) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 7, size = 1.3, colour = "darkorange") +
  labs(title = "PCA scree plot- Variance explanation heavily found in PCA1",
       subtitle = "With variance concentration, choosing 3 principle components seems reasonable despite elbow at 7",
       x = NULL)

As part of the PCA, Ill also review the component loadings for each variable. This provides insight into what information is captured in each principle component. To do so, Ive developed a faceted bar chart for each component. Overall, the factors do lend enough variability so each can be named and interpreted. These can be found below:

Factor interpretation and naming

- PCA1 attributes: Uniformly negative scores
- Name: Steady Dislike
- PCA2 attributes: Highest positive scores for trustworthy, prestige, emerging leader, easy access, and cool
- Name: Brand Perception
- PCA3 attributes: Highest positive scores for service and product related features (clear comms, customer service, easy application, etc.). Additionally, low on brand perception valus
- Name: Product and Features Utility
as.data.frame(brand_pca$loadings[,1:3]) %>%
  rownames_to_column(var = "variable") %>%
  rename_all(function(x) gsub(pattern = "Comp.", 
                              replacement = "PCA",

       subtitle = "Factor interpretation- PCA1: Steady Dislike, PCA2: Brand Perception, PCA3: Product and Features Utility",
       y = "pca loadings",

With the new components named, Ive put together a train and test split with the factor scores so a linear model can be developed. These are used the same way the initial predictors are so Ive also added the preferences ratings back in so the model can be cast using one data set.

The summary shows significant coefficients for all three variables, though the product utility is a matter of interpretation. The strength of evidence is right at the normal .05 alpha level but, Im giving it a pass because it adds further inferential interpretability to the model.

The slope coefficients are far more interpretable here owing to the transformation and seem intuitive. Both brand perception and product utility are associated with higher preference ratings while the steady dislike feature is negative. Between brand and product utility, the perception component has a higher slope coefficient as well. The models R2 is about .265, which is a slight drop from the initial linear attempt (.283).

brand_factors <- brand_pca$scores %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  select(1:3) %>%
  rename(Steady_Dislike = "Comp.1",
         Brand_Perception = "Comp.2",
         Product_Utility = "Comp.3") %>%
  mutate(preference_rating = cc_brands$preference_rating,
         respondent = cc_brands$respondent)

pca_train <- brand_factors %>%

pca_test <- brand_factors %>%

brand_pca_lm <- lm(preference_rating ~ Steady_Dislike + 
                     Brand_Perception + 
                     Product_Utility, 
                   data = pca_train)

While the pca regression helps with coefficient interpretation, it does not enhance the models predictive capabilities. This is because the predictors are only being compressed and represented in a different mathematical form, which means no new information is added. In fact, the pca model has slightly less variance being explained.

Reviewing the mean absolute error (MAE) for both the train and test still shows debatable predictive powers. The test MAE is about 3.26, which means each prediction is off by that many points (on average). The initial preference ratings only have an 11 point scale so this isnt great. For example, a perfect 11 might be predicted at 7.8, a value which tells a different customer brand preference story.

That said, this accuracy threshold would be best reviewed with the business for utility. If the values are broadly accurate for a consumer, the prediction might have marketing power. Overall though, I still think the pca model was more useful for getting a better understanding of the relationship between brand attribute ratings and preferences, rather than prediction. Here, the inferential component far outweighs the forward looking aspect.

data.frame(
  model = c("train", "test"),
  mae = c(
    mae(actual = pca_train$preference_rating, 
        predicted = brand_pca_lm$fitted.values),
    mae(actual = pca_test$preference_rating, 
        predicted = predict(brand_pca_lm, pca_test))
  )
) %>% custom_kable()

In an attempt to get better predictive results, I also developed a linear mixed effects model with the pca data. The addition of random effects for each respondent introduces individual coefficients alongside the group fixed effects. The new method introduces some prediction gains, though the increase from about 3.2 to 3 MAE is modest.

brand_mixed <- lmer(preference_rating ~ Steady_Dislike + 
                      Brand_Perception + 
                      Product_Utility + 
                      (1 + Steady_Dislike + 
                         Brand_Perception +
                         Product_Utility | respondent), 
                    data = pca_train)

data.frame(
  model = c("train", "test"),
  mae = c(
    mae(actual = pca_train$preference_rating, 
        predicted = predict(brand_mixed, pca_train)),
    mae(actual = pca_test$preference_rating, 
        predicted = predict(brand_mixed, pca_test))
  )
) %>% custom_kable()
model mae
train 2.660446
test 3.000280

Confirmatory Structural Equation Modelling

The other very real product of beginning with the inferential statistical modelling was developing a general hypothesis for how brand attribute ratings might be connected with preferences. This theory can be tested further using structural equation modelling (SEM), which is used to theorize causal relationships and the general pathways between measured and latent variables. The technique is confirmatory, meaning it can be used to advance a theory thats been developed using some subject matter expertise. Here, Ill be using the initial empirical result to further formulate how brand ratings and preference might be linked.

The modelling set up here differs from a more traditional statistical approach in R. SEM requires developing exogenous, endogenous, and latent variables. Exogenous variables do not have any causal elements represented and stand as the origin in the model. For the model Ill develop, my basic hypothesis is that preference rating (here a latent exogenous variable) is an amalgamation of several contributing latent factors.

This hypothesis stems from the factor analysis. Factor one showed a general brand and product dislike while factor two and three highlighted brand perceptions and product utility. Unfortunately, the first principle component does not seem to provide any wider marketing interpretation but, the others represent ideas which can be formalized as latent variables in the SEM.

However, I wanted to further refine the initial factors from the pca as well. For this, I theorized that the product utility could be divided into general service features (channel access) and business services (easy business financing). In the same vein, I retained brand perception as a factor but, also included a latent variable for product attitudes, which are more finite than a broad brand sentiment. These four latent variables, also called factors, form the basis of the measurement model and are linked to known brand attribute ratings.

Putting this together yields a three level SEM with five latent variables. The SEM paths are visualized below. As seen, brand preference (denoted as PR for preference) is informed by service features, brand perceptions, product attributes, and business services. In turn, these are linked to the predictors from the survey. Circles denote the latent variables while squares are measured endogenous variables.

brand_model <- "
#Service Features
SF =~ easy_access + channel_access + personalize_service + 
  rewards_for_good + easy_application + customer_service + clear_comms + account_infosec + quick_app_approval + best_prod_rates + dual_recognition

#Brand Perceptions
BP =~ cool + emerging_leader + innovative + prestige + trustworthy

#Product Attitudes
PA =~ my_best_interests + feel_valued + life_easier + reasonable_fees +
  fair_treatment + good_value

#Business Services
BS =~ products_for_bus + bus_cash_flow + responsive_bus_needs +
  business_advisor + understand_bus_probs + solves_bus_probs + bus_rewards_program +
  easy_bus_finance + easy_bus_invest

#Overall latent arrangement for Preference Rating (PR)
PR =~ SF + BS + BP + PA
"

brand_sem <- sem(model = brand_model, 
                 data = cc_brands,
                 meanstructure = T, 
                 std.lv = T)  

semPaths(object = brand_sem, whatLabels = "std", rotation = 2)

With the model estimated, its essential to work through the SEM parameters to ascertain what insights can be revealed about the relationship between the latent and measured variables. Broadly speaking, Im trying to better understand the confirmatory properties of the model with a focus on how brand ratings are linked to credit card preferences.

Ive developed a helpful summary function for the model parameter estimates, sem_param_review, which Im using below. The function filters all the model parameters related to one of the latent regressions (~= indicates is measured by) (Hartman, 2017). This extracts the factor loadings for each latent variable, which are akin to the regression coefficients.

The first table for service features shows positive coefficients (est column) for all the included endogenous variables ranging from .074 to .069. This seems to indicate all the included measured variables have a positive effect on the latent factor. Account information security seems to have the largest effect but, is only marginally larger than many other variables.

sem_param_review <- function(model, latent_var){
  parameterestimates(object = model) %>% 
  filter(op == "=~" & lhs == latent_var) %>% 
  arrange(desc(est)) %>%
  custom_kable()
}

Outside of the parameter estimates, its also important to examine the model residuals. In structural equation modelling, this means reviewing. The residuals function returns a correlation matrix for all the measured variables. Since the model suggests the expected relationship amongst variables, reviewing the results and comparing them to the actual values forms the residuals (ibid). The idea is that if there is a noticeable difference between the expected and actual correlations (around .1 or higher), there may be model fit issues.

Below, Ive used apply in conjunction with max to find the largest residuals. Here, rewards for being a good customer and the business rewards program show the largest correlation indicating there might be something between these two variables not captured by the model. Whats interesting is these capture a similar marketing idea but, are represented under two separate latent factors owing to the personal versus business split. Similarly, the next two for easy and quick applications are also related variables, though these fall under the same factor. Overall though, the residuals appear reasonable, which is a first indication that there might be a good model fit.

residuals(brand_sem, type = "cor")$cov %>%
  apply(., 2, max) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  rownames_to_column(var = "variable") %>%
  rename(residual_cor = ".") %>%
  arrange(desc(residual_cor)) %>%
  slice(1:6) %>%
  custom_kable()
variable residual_cor
rewards_for_good 0.0547735
bus_rewards_program 0.0547735
easy_application 0.0400734
quick_app_approval 0.0400734
best_prod_rates 0.0351433
reasonable_fees 0.0351433

To further confirm the model fit, Ive developed a table with three commonly cited fit metrics. Starting with the first value, Comparative Fit Index (CFI) is used to measure if the model fits the data better than a baseline null model. The target values here are being greater than .9. As seen, the CFI value is .966, which notes a good fit.

Root mean square error of approximation (RMSEA) evaluates the approximation error for residuals. Essentially, this helps measure how closely the model patterns resemble the data. The baseline target is less than .08 which is observed here.

The final value is the chi-squared p-value, which also assesses overall model fit by discrepancy between the sample and fitted covariance matrices (Cornell, 2018). The p-value is well below a .05 alpha but, with a sample size this large, the test should inherently be small. I think the first two metrics are likely more relevant in this case. These metrics all indicate that the model shows good fit.

fitMeasures(object = brand_sem, 
            fit.measures = c("cfi", "rmsea", "pvalue")) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  rownames_to_column(var = "fit_measure") %>%
  rename(value = ".") %>%
  mutate(value = round(value, 3)) %>%
  custom_kable()

As a final model check, the lavaan package has a function for reviewing possible improvements for SEMs. Most of the table shows places where extra covariances between variables should be added (as denoted by the ~~ operator). For example, one modification suggestion is adding a further covariance term for easy application and quick application approval. Im largely ignoring these because most of these fall under the same latent variable to begin with.

However, three modifications do appeal to me here. The table shows adding customer service, best product rates, and dual recognition (i.e.recognizing a person and a business) to product attitudes. As a rule of thumb, the model is developed using some theory ahead of time, which suggests that these modifications might be viewed with a critical eye. That said, I think the suggestions surrounding product attitudes make sense in a marketing context and that the variables could reasonably be compiled under attitudes factor. A consumer could easily view custom service, the best rates, or dual recognition as attitudes.

As such, Ill develop the new SEM with the three changes and evaluate the fit impact. All the metrics improve relative to the first model which is an encouraging sign.

mod_brand_model <- "
#Service Features
SF =~ easy_access + channel_access + personalize_service + 
  rewards_for_good + easy_application + clear_comms + account_infosec + quick_app_approval

#Brand Perceptions
BP =~ cool + emerging_leader + innovative + prestige + trustworthy

#Product Attitudes
PA =~ my_best_interests + feel_valued + life_easier + reasonable_fees +
  fair_treatment + good_value + dual_recognition + best_prod_rates + customer_service

#Business Services
BS =~ products_for_bus + bus_cash_flow + responsive_bus_needs +
  business_advisor + understand_bus_probs + solves_bus_probs + bus_rewards_program +
  easy_bus_finance + easy_bus_invest

#Overall latent arrangement for Preference Rating (PR)
PR =~ SF + BS + BP + PA
"

modified_brand_sem <- sem(model = mod_brand_model, 
                          data = cc_brands,
                          meanstructure = T, 
                          std.lv = T)

fitMeasures(object = modified_brand_sem, 
            fit.measures = c("cfi", "rmsea", "pvalue")) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  rownames_to_column(var = "fit_measure") %>%
  rename(value = ".") %>%

  custom_kable()

As a final confirmation, I wanted to conduct an anova to verify the five factor model is preferable to a smaller arrangement. This stems from my original decision to split brand perception and product utilities into four factor as opposed to leaving them as larger categories. Below, Ive developed this smaller three factor model.

three_brand_model <- "
#Product Utilities
PU =~ easy_access + channel_access + personalize_service + 
rewards_for_good + easy_application + clear_comms + account_infosec +
quick_app_approval + products_for_bus + bus_cash_flow + responsive_bus_needs +
business_advisor + understand_bus_probs + solves_bus_probs + bus_rewards_program +
easy_bus_finance + easy_bus_invest


#Brand and Product Perceptions
BPP =~ cool + emerging_leader + innovative + prestige + trustworthy + 
my_best_interests + feel_valued + life_easier + reasonable_fees +
fair_treatment + good_value + dual_recognition + best_prod_rates + customer_service


#Overall latent arrangement for Preference Rating (PR)
PR =~ BPP + PU
"

three_factor_sem <- sem(model = three_brand_model, 
                        data = cc_brands,
                        meanstructure = T, 
                        std.lv = T)

To compare both SEMs, Ive developed an anova table. The results are clear and the larger five factor model is preferable. It has a much lower AIC and the chi-square test is highly significant as well.

anova(modified_brand_sem, three_factor_sem)

Final business analysis

Using a mixture of traditional statistical modelling and structural equation models, I think Ive made positive strides to quantify the relationship between brand attribute ratings and consumer preference. The regression models provided mixed predictive results, which would need validation with a marketing group for wider business utility, but offered a strong empirical base for developing the SEM. The pca regression indicated that both brand perception and product utility contribute towards higher preference ratings. This result was confirmed and expanded using the confirmatory SEM, which further added that preferences are driven by service features and product attitudes as well.

Since SEM provides an empirical option for confirming a theory, I wanted to see how the four latent factors look when applied to the initial data. For this, I added another feature to the data which categorizes which endogenous variables fall under each latent factor. The intention is to see how the look when evaluating the average brand attribute scores by card company.

The plot below shows these scores coloured by the factors. What immediately stands out is the highest average scores tend to be service features, which was the most important SEM factor. Theres a fair mix after the top scores but, the scores look consistent with the factors. Interestingly, the best scores for high performing brands seem to have account information security as the top score, which was also the most impactful coefficient in the SF latent model. I think this adds a nice link between the theory and practical results.

SF <- c("easy_access", "channel_access", "personalize_service", "rewards_for_good",
        "easy_application", "clear_comms", "account_infosec",
        "quick_app_approval") 

BP <- c("cool", "emerging_leader", "innovative", "prestige", "trustworthy")

PA <- c("customer_service", "best_prod_rates", "dual_recognition", "my_best_interests",
        "feel_valued", "life_easier", "reasonable_fees", "fair_treatment", "good_value")

BS <- c("products_for_bus", "bus_cash_flow", "responsive_bus_needs", "business_advisor",
        "understand_bus_probs", "solves_bus_probs", "bus_rewards_program", 
        "easy_bus_finance", "easy_bus_invest")

cc_brands %>%
  select(3, 8:38) %>%
  group_by(brand) %>%
  summarise_if(is.numeric, function(x) mean(x)) %>%
  gather(key = "variable", value = "value", -brand) %>%
  mutate(brand = factor(brand, levels = c("Other_sec", "Amex", "Citibank", "BoA",
                                          "Chase", "Wells_Fargo", "HSBC",
                                          "Other_prim", "Advanta")),
         sem_factor = case_when(
           variable %in% SF ~ "service_feature",
           variable %in% BP ~ "brand_perception",
           variable %in% PA ~ "product_attitude",
           variable %in% BS ~ "business_service"
             )
        ) %>%
  mutate(sem_factor = factor(sem_factor, levels = c("service_feature", 
                                                    "product_attitude",
                                                    "business_service", 
                                                    "brand_perception")),
         variable = reorder(variable, value)) %>%
  filter(value != 4) %>%
  ggplot(aes(variable, value, colour = sem_factor, fill = sem_factor)) +
  geom_col() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 1.5, colour = "firebrick1", size = 1.3, alpha = .75) +
  coord_flip() +
  facet_wrap(facets = "brand") +
  labs(title = "Average brand rating by question in credit card preference set with SEM factor colouring",
       subtitle = "Higest average scores seem to conform to SEM factor importance with service features most strongly linked to preference",
       x = NULL,
       y = "brand rating avg")

The results seem to indicate that product positioning should lean on how the brands service features might help a consumer. Introducing campaigns around these features seems like a good choice for underperforming brands Outside of the immediate marketing implications, this result would be useful for shaping business operations as well given the features are tangible services offered by a firm. Overall, this work cold help refine both product positioning and operational services.
